Chapter 12: Multivariate Regression

Todays class will be based on Chapter 12: Multiple Regression. Have you read it? We will be using data on college characteristics from the IPEDS Database and the Scorecard created by the Department of Education, gathered via the Opportunity Insights project. The codebook with explanations for each variable is here. We will be trying to figure out what characteristics of a college are associated with the 2011 median income of students, earnings, 10 years after they graduate. The other data faculty, the average faculty salary; sat, the average SAT score; tier, the type of college; public, the private/public status; and price, tuition is reported as of 2001.

Scene 4

Prompt: Now lets quantify these relationships between the two explanatory variables and the outcome variable. Fit a multiple regression model for earnings using sat and faculty as the explanatory variables. Write a bullet point interpreting each of the three values in the estimate column. Do not use any interaction terms in the regression (yet).

earnings_model <- lm(earnings ~ sat + faculty, data = x)

earnings_model %>%
  tidy(conf.int = TRUE) %>%
  select(term, estimate, conf.low, conf.high)
## # A tibble: 3 x 4
##   term         estimate  conf.low conf.high
##   <chr>           <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept) -2591.    -7092.     1910.   
## 2 sat            24.5      19.2      29.7  
## 3 faculty         0.385     0.335     0.436

First, the intercept value is -2590.98. This intercept represents the earnings for an individual who has sat score of and their facultys income is $0, meaning they are not in college.

Second, for every increase of one dollar in faculty earnings, there is an associated increase of on average $24.48 in the earnings of the student.

Third, taking into account all other explanatory variables in our model, for every increase of one point in SAT scores, there is an associated increase of, on average, $0.38 in students earnings.

Scene 6

Prompt: Imagine that you are the university president. Theres a global pandemic that is causing serious financial damage to the school endowment, and in response, you want to cut the financial aid budget. However, because many academically talented students will go to whichever school gives them the best financial aid package, slashing the financial aid budget will cause the average SAT score to decrease from 1400 to 1300. Apply the Rubin Causal Model to frame the causal effect of this policy change on the median earnings of students 10 years from now. Write down the units, the treatments, and the outcomes. Define the causal effect of the policy change on median earnings. What is the fundamental problem of causal inference? What must you assume for this causal model to make a causal claim?

Applying the Rubin Causal Model to this dataset:

Unit: School/college

Treatment: Cutting the financial aid budget (or average SAT score)

Outcomes: Earnings of students 10 years after they enter college

Fundamental problem of causal inference: We cannot know the outcomes for each university under each treatment, because only one option can actually occur.

In order for this to be a causal claim, the treatment should be randomized to minimize confounding factors.
